Time Complexity: number of paths * time complexity for each path.

**Using Strings:**
```
class Solution {
    List<String> res = new ArrayList();
    public List<String> binaryTreePaths(TreeNode root) {
        if (root == null)
            return res;
        binaryTreePaths(root,"");
        return res;
    }

    public void binaryTreePaths(TreeNode root, String str){
        str+= (str.length()==0) ? String.valueOf(root.val): "->"+String.valueOf(root.val);
        if(root.left==null && root.right==null) res.add(str);
        if(root.left!=null) binaryTreePaths(root.left,str);
        if(root.right!=null) binaryTreePaths(root.right,str);
    }

}
```

Well balanced tree Case:

There will N/2 leaf nodes and max path length would be O(logn).
In every path we traverse, we are adding a char to string, in every such operation a string is allocated (and copied, due to String immutability) for each node in this path, not just the leaves.
Hence the complexity for a single path would be 1+ 2+ .....+ logn = O((logN)^2).
Total complexity is O(N/2)*O(logN)^2) =  **O(N x (logN)^2).**

Nodes in Straight Line Case:

Here there would be a single leaf path, which is of length N.
Hence time complexity for this path: 1+2+3+..n = O(N^2).
Since we have a single path here, Total Complexity is =  **O(N^2).**

**Using String Builder:**

```
class Solution {
    List<String> res = new ArrayList();
    public List<String> binaryTreePaths(TreeNode root) {
        if (root == null)
            return res;
        binaryTreePaths(root,new StringBuilder());
        return res;
    }

    public void binaryTreePaths(TreeNode root, StringBuilder sb){        
        if(root==null) return;

        int len = sb.length();
        sb.append(root.val);

        if(root.left==null && root.right==null) 
            res.add(sb.toString());
        else{
            sb.append("->");
            binaryTreePaths(root.left,sb);
            binaryTreePaths(root.right,sb);
        }
       sb.setLength(len);
    }
}
```

